In considering appropriate treatment changes there are multiple lines of evidence that are available to us in choosing regimens that are favourable in terms of fractionation or provide us with confidence to advise patents not to proceed with radiotherapy. Therapies that have been considered standard of care based on evidence should be reconsidered in the context of the current situation. Some of these are documented in Table 2
. It is important to consider that risk–benefit is unique to each patient, disease, and the impact of the pandemic on workforce and risk all of which will change over time. A balance must be struck at each institution. We have sought to provide fair guidelines for specific situations below. Evidence link and brief dose constraint guidance are given for situations where palliative treatment (Table 3
) and radical treatment (Table 4
) may be altered. Table 5
lists therapies that may be delayed.
